1. Create and Set Up the Environment
Run these commands in your EC2 terminal:

bash
# Ensure the full Python environment toolset is installed
sudo apt update && sudo apt install python3-full -y

# Create a virtual environment named .venv in your project folder
python3 -m venv .venv

# Activate the environment
source .venv/bin/activate

# Install the required kernel library inside the environment
pip install ipykernel

-----

2. Connect VS Code to the Environment

Open your .ipynb notebook file inside VS Code.

Look at the top-right corner of the notebook window and click Select Kernel (or click on the existing Python version displayed there).

Choose Python Environments... from the dropdown.

Select the .venv environment you just created.

    (Ctrl + Shift + P => Python: Select Interpreter => Refresh icon => Look for your virtual environment path (it will show something like ./.venv/bin/python) and click on it
    OR
    Enter interpreter path -> Find... -> Type or navigate to the path of your virtual environment. )

VS Code will now use this isolated environment to run your notebook cells without triggering any system errors.

